<h1><a href="unsubscribe">Underachieving unsubscribe confirmation pages</a></h1>

<p>Why do unsubscribe confirmation pages always look like this<sup>1</sup>:</p>

<p><img src="http://dl.dropbox.com/u/1276566/umtitled/post_images/unsubscribe.jpg" alt="Unsubscribe"></p>

<p>It's as if the idea of a mailing-list recipient unsubscribing from an email campaign is so outlandish that only bare minimum effort can be spared to build this function. Or maybe it was such an afterthought that the developer had no time to even wrap the confirmation message in the site's template<sup>2</sup>. Actually, I'll bet the boss's nephew is an aspiring <em>computer programmer</em> and hey, why not let the boy bang out a few lines of code?</p>

<p>I'll tell you why not: it's unprofessional and frankly, embarrassing (for you). Conceivably, this is the last chance your business will have to keep me as a customer (or reader, or whatever)... and you're going to blow it with a context devoid message?! Seeing something like this just strengthens my decision to unsubscribe. It solidifies my impression of your company as unprofessional and uncaring. And hey, now I'm really glad I left.</p>

<p>But what if you were to give some thought to the delivery of that message? Maybe remind me that your business is worth my time. At least wrap the page in your template... there's a good chance that I haven't been to your site in a long time. It might look fresh and new... and that might be enough to make me stick around.</p>

<p>Just do something better than this. Please. You're making us all<sup>3</sup> look bad.</p>

<hr>
<ol>
<li>Okay, they don't always look like this. But in my experience, most do.</li>
<li>Looks like the developer in the above image had some free cycles and went that extra mile with an <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> and a <code>&lt;p&gt;</code>.</li>
<li>By  "us all" I mean those of us who butter our bread by making stuff for the internet.</li>
</ol>

