<h1><a href="capital-i">We all live in a capital I, in the middle of the desert, in the center of the sky</a></h1>

<p>My son is just about the right age to start weening him onto Sesame Street. Thankfully, YouTube is bursting at the seams with full-length episodes... many of which are from, what I consider to be, the heyday of the series: the 1970s.</p>

<p>I extracted the following segment from <a href="http://muppet.wikia.com/wiki/Episode_0514">episode 514</a><sup>1</sup>  (1972). It's entitled, "<a href="http://muppet.wikia.com/wiki/I_in_the_Sky">I in the Sky</a>". And it's bizarre.</p>

<iframe width="600" height="450" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/t6-LsCTFtX4?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<p>In case you missed them, here are the lyrics:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>We all live in a capital I, in the middle of the desert, in the center of the sky. And all day long we polish on the I, to keep it clean and shiny so it brightens up the sky.</p>
  
  <p>Rubbing it here and scrubbing it there. Polishing the I so high in the air. </p>
  
  <p>As we work we sing a lively tune. It is great to be so happy on a busy afternoon. And when we're through with the day's only chore, we go into the I and we close the door. </p>
  
  <p>Capital I. Capital I. Capital I. Capital I. </p>
</blockquote>

<p><em>Okay. Right. Umm. What?</em> My sentiments exactly. Curiosity got the better of me and I did a little digging<sup>2</sup>. Here's what I found:</p>

<ol>
<li>This is not the first appearance of the "I in the Sky" song. Apparently, it first aired in episode 427. <em>Who cares.</em> But more interestingly...</li>
<li>...the song reappears some <strong>35 years later</strong> (in 2007) when the imaginatively named character, Baby Bear, sings "the chorus of the song as he draws a capital I"<sup>3</sup>.</li>
</ol>
<p>35 years later. Wow. That's awesome. In fact, that's enough time for a child who grew up with Sesame Street in the 70s to <em>be</em> grown up and watch the song reappear in the 2007 episode with <em>their</em> child. Imagine the WTF-factor if that were to happen.</p>

<p>Go ahead, imagine it. I'll wait.</p>

<hr>
<ol>
<li>Episode 514 has no special significance. It was simply the first one I pulled down from <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H7DTksUfDaI">YouTube</a>. As it turns out, it's pretty awesome (as awesome as a Sesame Street episode can be... which, as it turns out, is pretty darn awesome). This particular episode features Stevie Wonder, by the way.</li>
<li>Don't be too impressed; there's a whole <a href="http://muppet.wikia.com/wiki/Category:Sesame_Street_Episode_Guide">massive wiki</a> devoted to Sesame Street episodes.</li>
<li>If anyone knows where I might be able to watch that segment (or episode), I'd be eternally grateful... or at least, reasonably appreciative.</li>
</ol>

