<h1><a href="wwdc-2012-missing-announcement">WWDC 2012's missing announcement</a></h1>

<p>WWDC 2012 has brought some impressive changes to Apple's laptop armada. Yet, there's still something missing...</p>

<p>Despite the fact that not one rumor site<sup>1</sup> was reporting this, I was half-expecting to see 3G brought to the MacBook line... in the same way it's in the iPad. Imagine, if you will, a 3G, month-to-month option in something like the MacBook Air. A marriage made in heaven, as far as I'm concerned. </p>

<p>Just this past week, I used an iPad with 3G for the first time. I was traveling to and from a conference<sup>2</sup> by train. It was a delightful experience to have capable internet access during the journey<sup>3</sup>... but my delight multiplied when I realized that I wasn't beholden to the shitty hotel wifi<sup>4</sup>. </p>

<p>My point is simply that using 3G on the iPad was a great experience. The only part that was suboptimal was the iPad itself. Don't get me wrong, I love me some iPad! Still, I'm a laptop holdout. Yep. I'm a card-carrying member of the ever decreasing populous of those who feel that they can be significantly more productive on a laptop<sup>5</sup>. Thus, bringing 3G to an ultra-portable Mac (like the 11 inch Air) would, in my mind, be a completely natural fit.</p>

<p>I can only assume that Apple has thought of this. And therefore, I can only assume that there's a technical hurdle preventing the inclusion of cellular data. Maybe it adds too much bulk? Could it be a licensing issue? Dunno. Either way, its absence is shocking<sup>6</sup>.</p>

<hr>
<ol>
<li>That I read, anyway.</li>
<li>The <a href="http://www.nmc.org/">New Media Consortium</a> conference, in case you're wondering. It was awesome, in case you're wondering.</li>
<li>On something bigger than my iPhone.</li>
<li>Hyatt Cambridge, in case you're wondering... although it could easily be any hotel. Let's face it, here in the US, hotel wifi is just shitty. The hotel itself was gorgeous though. Recommended... even despite the wifi.</li>
<li>Although, the gap is narrowing.</li>
<li>Yes, shocking.</li>
</ol>

